'''Suseribime''' (須勢理毘売, 須世理毘売, 須世理姫, 須世理比売, 和加須世理比売命) is a female deity in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== Overview == In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, she is named as '''須勢理毘売命''' (Suseribime-no-Mikoto) or '''須世理毘売''' (Suseribime). In the {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, she is referred to as '''須世理姫''' (Suserihime), and in the {{ill|Izumo Fudoki|ja|Izumo Province 風土記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, she is described as '''和加須世理比売命''' (Waka Suserihime-no-Mikoto).
Although her origins are unclear, Suseribime is the daughter of {{ill|Susanoo|ja|須佐之男命|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the principal wife of {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== Mythology == In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Suseribime resides in the {{ill|Ne-no-Kuni|ja|根の国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (the underworld) with her father, Susanoo. She encounters Ōnamuchi (Ōkuninushi) when he flees from the pursuit of the {{ill|Yaso-no-Kami|ja|八十神|1=Yasogami|lt=Yasogami (80 gods)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The two marry immediately. Upon returning home, Suseribime introduces Ōnamuchi to her father. Susanoo tests him by placing him in perilous situations, such as sleeping in a room filled with snakes, bees, and centipedes. Suseribime assists Ōnamuchi by providing him with enchanted items, such as the '''Hire''' (比礼), to help him survive.
Eventually, Ōnamuchi ties Susanoo’s hair to a pillar and escapes with Suseribime. As he departs, Susanoo names Ōnamuchi as "Ōkuninushi" and blesses their union, instructing him to build a grand palace and pacify the land.
Although Ōkuninushi had children with {{ill|Yakami-hime|ja|八上比売|1=Yagami-hime|qq=draft|qq=draft}} before meeting Suseribime, Yakami-hime feared Suseribime’s authority and left, entrusting their child, {{ill|Kimata-no-Kami|ja|木俣神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, to Ōkuninushi.
Later, Suseribime exhibits intense jealousy when Ōkuninushi courts {{ill|Numakawa-hime|ja|沼河比売|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Koshi Province|ja|越国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Despite her jealousy, the two reconcile and remain together.
== Analysis == The name "Suseri" may derive from "susu" (advance) and "susa" (rage), indicating her passionate nature. Her actions, whether helping her husband overcome trials or expressing jealousy, demonstrate her immense authority and influence as a deity.<ref>Shinchō Nihon Koten Shūsei, Kojiki</ref>
The story of Suseribime and Ōkuninushi fits the framework of a "marriage test" myth, where the groom undergoes trials set by the bride’s father. Successfully completing these trials signifies the groom’s worthiness.<ref name="bunken1">*Nihon Shinwa Jiten*, p. 182</ref>
== Shrines == Suseribime is often worshipped alongside Ōkuninushi. Notable shrines include: * {{ill|Izumo Taisha|ja|出雲大社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Izumo City, Shimane Prefecture) – Sub-shrine: Ōkami Ōgū Shrine * {{ill|Namesa Shrine|ja|那売佐神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Izumo City, Shimane Prefecture) * {{ill|Kasuga Taisha|ja|春日大社|1=Kasuga-taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Nara City, Nara Prefecture) – Sub-shrine: Meoto Daikokusha * {{ill|Kunikami Shrine|ja|國魂神社 (いわき市)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Iwaki City, Fukushima Prefecture) * {{ill|Sōja Shrine|ja|総社宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Okayama City, Okayama Prefecture) * {{ill|Bitchū Sōja Shrine|ja|備中国総社宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Sōja City, Okayama Prefecture)
